# Django Development Standards

## Core Principles

- Follow Django's "Convention over Configuration" philosophy
- Use Django's built-in features before creating custom solutions
- Maintain backward compatibility with Django 4.2+ as specified in pyproject.toml
- Follow Django's security best practices
- Use Django's ORM efficiently to avoid N+1 queries

## Model Guidelines

- Always inherit from appropriate base classes (TimeStampedMixin is already available)
- Use UUIDField as primary key for new models (following existing pattern)
- Define `__str__` methods for all models
- Use proper field types and constraints
- Add model-level validation when appropriate
- Use related_name for foreign keys to avoid conflicts

## View Guidelines

- Use class-based views for complex logic
- Use function-based views for simple operations
- Always handle exceptions gracefully
- Use Django's built-in authentication and permissions
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes
- Use Django's pagination for list views

## Settings Management

- Use the existing namespaced settings pattern (DJANGO_ERGO)
- Define defaults in DEFAULTS dictionary
- Use IMPORT_STRINGS for importable settings
- Document removed settings in REMOVED_SETTINGS
- Use environment variables for sensitive data

## URL Configuration

- Use meaningful URL names
- Group related URLs using include()
- Use path() over url() (Django 2.0+ style)
- Follow RESTful conventions where appropriate

## Testing

- Write tests for all models, views, and utilities
- Use Django's TestCase or TransactionTestCase
- Mock external dependencies
- Test both success and failure scenarios
- Maintain the current 97% coverage standard

## Code Quality

- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Use type hints for function parameters and return values
- Write docstrings for all public methods and classes
- Use Django's built-in validators
- Handle migrations properly

## Example

<example>
# Good Django model
class KnowledgeBase(TimeStampedMixin):
    """AI Knowledge base entry."""

    id = models.UUIDField(primary_key=True, default=uuid.uuid4, editable=False)
    title = models.CharField(max_length=255, help_text="Knowledge base title")
    content = models.TextField(help_text="Main content")
    tags = models.ManyToManyField('Tag', blank=True, related_name='knowledge_bases')

    class Meta:
        ordering = ['-created']
        verbose_name = "Knowledge Base Entry"
        verbose_name_plural = "Knowledge Base Entries"

    def __str__(self):
        return self.title
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Avoid - missing proper inheritance, no UUID, poor naming
class kb(models.Model):
    name = models.CharField(max_length=50)  # Too short
    data = models.TextField()  # Vague field name
    # Missing __str__ method
    # No help_text
    # No proper primary key
</example>
